1
00:00:02,579 --> 00:00:31,827
Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambodasa Namotasa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambodasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:33,088 --> 00:00:35,393
So I've chosen to look at compassion.

3
00:00:35,414 --> 00:00:47,779
So this is the last of our four Brahma Viharas, the dwelling place of the gods, of the highest gods, by which we mean these are the most beautiful mental states that we can achieve.

4
00:00:47,820 --> 00:00:51,146
So we've done love, done joy, done equanimity.

5
00:00:51,267 --> 00:00:53,832
So compassion is the last one.

6
00:00:54,232 --> 00:00:58,021
So I'd like to start with my own little story here.

7
00:00:58,040 --> 00:01:14,233
I went along the hippie trail around about the 70s, and I ended up in Calcutta during the Indo-Pakistan War, when Bangladesh got its liberation from West Pakistan.

8
00:01:14,212 --> 00:01:20,688
And every day for three weeks, when we were expecting bombers to come over, I used to go to this Sikh restaurant.

9
00:01:21,069 --> 00:01:26,444
And on the opposite side of the road, there was a woman with a huge goita, you know, under her chin.

10
00:01:27,144 --> 00:01:28,448
I passed that woman every day.

11
00:01:28,748 --> 00:01:29,792
I never gave her a penny.

12
00:01:31,763 --> 00:01:41,162
One day I came back and just as I turned around the corner, there was a little girl there who must have been well over seven, undernourished, looked very young.

13
00:01:41,844 --> 00:01:48,760
And she was squatted down chewing a dried out black banana skin.

14
00:01:49,971 --> 00:01:55,998
And she had this sort of self-possession, really, to cover her sex, because all she had was this little dress.

15
00:01:56,757 --> 00:01:58,239
And I walked straight past her, you see.

16
00:01:58,799 --> 00:02:08,188
So I've got these two images from this callow youth, and they're very difficult for me to remember them without a certain sense of pain.

17
00:02:08,528 --> 00:02:16,075
And, of course, the reason the pain is there, not simply because of seeing this sort of suffering, which I just had never seen before.

18
00:02:16,096 --> 00:02:17,818
I mean, there were...

19
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:23,764
There were sick people everywhere, lepers, people with elephantitis.

20
00:02:23,824 --> 00:02:25,548
I mean, they were there on the pavement.

21
00:02:26,549 --> 00:02:29,592
And of course, what pains is that I didn't respond.

22
00:02:29,612 --> 00:02:31,635
I didn't put a penny in that woman's hand.

23
00:02:31,756 --> 00:02:35,181
She sat there all day, completely emotionless with her hand out like that.

24
00:02:36,021 --> 00:02:40,768
And I didn't go out and buy a banana for this little girl, you see.

25
00:02:41,423 --> 00:02:50,147
So here we have a sort of a, what happens to us, what you feel is that you haven't responded.

26
00:02:50,207 --> 00:02:54,741
You haven't responded from a compassionate heart for whatever reason, you know.

27
00:02:55,750 --> 00:03:00,634
So it all begins with that connection, which we call empathy and sometimes sympathy.

28
00:03:00,655 --> 00:03:03,418
I just want to make a little distinction there.

29
00:03:03,598 --> 00:03:09,544
When we say, I mean, this is just arbitrary distinction because these words are used in different ways.

30
00:03:10,324 --> 00:03:23,157
Sympathy these days has some suggestion of pity, you know, but sympathy for me to make this distinction is when you have to imagine in a way what the person is suffering.

31
00:03:23,138 --> 00:03:25,544
So I've never been starving.

32
00:03:25,645 --> 00:03:27,730
I've been hungry, but then I've always had food.

33
00:03:28,453 --> 00:03:31,381
I've never been in a state where I'm actually starving, you know.

34
00:03:32,163 --> 00:03:37,157
And so all I can do is imagine what it must be like because I felt hungry.

35
00:03:37,257 --> 00:03:39,122
So there's a sort of connection there.

36
00:03:39,776 --> 00:03:43,366
But when it comes to, say, refugees, I've never been a refugee.

37
00:03:43,385 --> 00:03:53,793
I haven't a clue what it means to suddenly up and out your home, to find yourself on the road without much money, having to buy your way, sometimes being attacked.

38
00:03:53,832 --> 00:03:54,394
Who knows?

39
00:03:55,893 --> 00:04:02,304
So there's a point where there's a sympathy where you have to imagine what the person is going.

40
00:04:02,824 --> 00:04:07,192
And there's empathy where you've actually had an experience which connects you.

41
00:04:07,712 --> 00:04:13,802
So that's just a little distinction I want to make so that we're clear when we're sympathizing and we're actually empathizing.

42
00:04:13,823 --> 00:04:16,567
Because I think sometimes we think we're empathizing.

43
00:04:16,548 --> 00:04:29,923
when actually we're imagining, which isn't, if it all leads to the same place, which is a compassionate act, a compassionate word, I mean, there's not really a problem, but I thought I'd hang on to that little definition just for clarity's sake.

44
00:04:30,783 --> 00:04:44,259
So then the Buddha himself uses a word, anukampa, and the word anu, the prefix anu, is a suggestion of movement towards, movement.

45
00:04:44,240 --> 00:04:46,766
And the Kampa actually means trembling.

46
00:04:47,206 --> 00:05:00,139
So he says, whatever a teacher can do for his students out of the Anu Kampa, out of this connection with his students, I have done for you.

47
00:05:01,317 --> 00:05:08,132
So this anukampa is that point where you have that sense in your own heart of the suffering of the other.

48
00:05:08,172 --> 00:05:16,690
It's that connection, you know, whether it's imaginative sympathy or whether it's empathic connection.

49
00:05:17,271 --> 00:05:19,798
And...

50
00:05:20,891 --> 00:05:24,877
The other word we use is karuna, which actually has its root in doing.

51
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:42,747
The word in the Sanskrit, kra, I think it's ka, means doing, but it was also used for holy, it was part of the rituals of the Vedas.

52
00:05:42,767 --> 00:05:46,713
So you get this word karuna, which is actually the action.

53
00:05:46,694 --> 00:05:50,819
You might call it the sacrifice or the sacrament.

54
00:05:51,480 --> 00:05:52,982
Okay.

55
00:05:53,002 --> 00:06:05,819
So when we have responded to somebody's suffering, no matter what it is, you know, the smallest to the most awful.

56
00:06:06,680 --> 00:06:11,367
That's a mosquito, by the way, that I'm walking away.

57
00:06:11,406 --> 00:06:12,307
There are two modes.

58
00:06:12,487 --> 00:06:14,630
One is passive and one is active.

59
00:06:14,651 --> 00:06:16,312
So in the passive mode,

60
00:06:16,732 --> 00:06:23,244
It's often good enough just to be with the person, you know, not even to say anything.

61
00:06:23,704 --> 00:06:33,242
I mean, an obvious case would be when the person is either extremely ill and is just there in bed and all you can do is actually accompany them.

62
00:06:33,622 --> 00:06:36,107
And of course, when somebody is dying.

63
00:06:36,086 --> 00:06:42,274
But I think what we come across when we have that sort of situation is our sense of powerlessness.

64
00:06:42,874 --> 00:06:45,377
And that's very difficult for us because we want to do something.

65
00:06:45,576 --> 00:06:48,079
You know, you want to do something.

66
00:06:48,100 --> 00:06:55,107
But, you know, if we are sensitive enough to the situation and to the person, I mean, you don't have to ask them for heaven's sake.

67
00:06:56,408 --> 00:07:00,593
Often it's good enough just to be with them, you know, just to accompany them.

68
00:07:01,601 --> 00:07:14,939
When it comes to compassionate action, when you're actually going to do something, then our tendency, I think, is to try and overdo, you know, and to slip into the error of the do-gooder.

69
00:07:15,680 --> 00:07:23,610
I mean, we've all got it in us, which is when we want to do the good we want to do for your benefit, whether you want it or not.

70
00:07:24,651 --> 00:07:27,113
So, of course, this really gets up people's noses.

71
00:07:27,334 --> 00:07:28,014
So,

72
00:07:29,175 --> 00:07:31,079
It was a good idea to ask them what they want to do.

73
00:07:31,781 --> 00:07:46,172
Even if what your suggestion is rejected, and even if you know that your suggestion would actually be the better thing to do, even so, we've got to pull back a bit and let the person who's suffering have the last say.

74
00:07:47,940 --> 00:08:00,997
But often when we do over-help like that, perhaps it's coming from some sort of inner feeling of wanting to be esteemed, to be loved, all the usual rubbish that we suffer from, you see.

75
00:08:07,105 --> 00:08:12,952
So now, it's often easier to say what...

76
00:08:13,168 --> 00:08:18,156
a virtue is by saying what it isn't, right?

77
00:08:18,197 --> 00:08:21,060
So we know it's not do-gooding, right?

78
00:08:21,401 --> 00:08:29,012
So these are, shall we say, reactions that we have when we come across suffering.

79
00:08:31,456 --> 00:08:38,366
The first one would be in a sort of extreme case where the person is really suffering.

80
00:08:38,346 --> 00:08:43,462
And there you've got to have that sort of sense of courage to be with them.

81
00:08:43,543 --> 00:08:50,043
It's very difficult if the person is really in a lot of pain, especially when they're dying.

82
00:08:50,462 --> 00:09:01,043
I read a book about this poor woman who was screaming, screaming every time she, you know, towards the end of her life.

83
00:09:01,345 --> 00:09:10,142
And eventually the doctor decided to sedate her, you know, with the obviously the permission of the family.

84
00:09:10,121 --> 00:09:15,548
So it often takes a bit of courage to be with somebody who's in real pain or suffering.

85
00:09:16,929 --> 00:09:31,245
There are certain situations which might be a work situation, but it can be somebody you're looking after where you have reactions of disgust, where they're sick, where they're suffering from diarrhea.

86
00:09:31,365 --> 00:09:35,370
All the impurities of the body manifest.

87
00:09:35,350 --> 00:09:43,058
And somehow you have to recognize that is the disgust and yet still come from the heart of compassion.

88
00:09:44,441 --> 00:09:51,789
We can often be caught unawares, you know, like somebody has found somebody's asked us to do something and we sort of feel messed up.

89
00:09:51,870 --> 00:09:56,294
You know, I had my day carefully planned and now they want me to do this and want me to do that.

90
00:09:56,544 --> 00:10:00,971
especially within a family, and you can feel yourself being angry about that.

91
00:10:01,331 --> 00:10:10,462
So again, it's being aware of these negative emotions that come up, these negative mental states, and still focusing on what you can do for the person.

92
00:10:12,424 --> 00:10:24,561
Sometimes a person hurts themselves, an accident, for instance, and you might be wanting to blame them, so stupid, how could you do that?

93
00:10:24,845 --> 00:10:39,006
I remember I once had an assistant here who put the ladder up against the gutter on the decking and the ladder slipped and he just fell flat onto his face almost.

94
00:10:39,206 --> 00:10:41,730
Luckily, there was nothing but a bit of a bruise.

95
00:10:42,272 --> 00:10:46,177
But I could hear myself saying, well, that was stupid, wasn't it?

96
00:10:47,600 --> 00:10:48,380
But I didn't say it.

97
00:10:48,600 --> 00:10:49,201
No, I didn't say it.

98
00:10:49,221 --> 00:10:49,763
No, no.

99
00:10:49,783 --> 00:10:53,568
No, I then went up and made sure that he was okay.

100
00:10:54,022 --> 00:10:55,322
But you've got to be careful.

101
00:10:56,543 --> 00:11:00,788
You can, of course, if it's somebody close to you, feel quite overcome by grief.

102
00:11:00,927 --> 00:11:05,052
And that can have a sort of an immobilizing effect, you know.

103
00:11:05,451 --> 00:11:15,100
And again, it's just resting with that and trying to sort of come above it, come above it and to connect with the person.

104
00:11:15,961 --> 00:11:21,765
And that way, I think we can keep these emotional states at bay, you might say.

105
00:11:21,865 --> 00:11:24,028
You might have to deal with them afterwards.

106
00:11:24,008 --> 00:11:29,035
but not while you're in some sort of situation with them, you know.

107
00:11:29,616 --> 00:11:37,448
I mean, you can understand things like panic, you know, when, so we say a child hurts itself and the parents sort of just panic, you know.

108
00:11:37,889 --> 00:11:41,154
Well, obviously that doesn't help, doesn't help the child.

109
00:11:42,518 --> 00:11:51,552
But it's again, hopefully bringing that mindfulness, that connection with our own hearts and that reaction, you know,

110
00:11:51,532 --> 00:11:54,816
and then to rise above it and respond.

111
00:11:56,938 --> 00:11:58,861
There's pity.

112
00:11:59,001 --> 00:12:00,945
That's another one, which isn't particularly nice.

113
00:12:01,365 --> 00:12:09,196
And that's coming from a superior position, often because we're trying to guard ourselves against actually connecting with what's happening.

114
00:12:09,697 --> 00:12:10,977
You know, it's, oh, poor thing.

115
00:12:11,018 --> 00:12:12,519
You know, I feel so sorry for you.

116
00:12:12,561 --> 00:12:14,383
You know, I know how you're feeling.

117
00:12:16,438 --> 00:12:26,793
So often we find that that's because we're a bit afraid of facing our own possible sickness and eventual death, you know.

118
00:12:26,833 --> 00:12:37,308
There can be a sort of a sense of relief, you know, like when somebody has a serious illness, as we have in our family.

119
00:12:37,349 --> 00:12:40,634
And you can sort of, first of all, feel the fear.

120
00:12:40,653 --> 00:12:42,716
Well, if it's in the family, I might get it.

121
00:12:43,438 --> 00:12:47,486
And then a sense of relief, oh, it's not me, you see.

122
00:12:47,547 --> 00:12:57,927
So we have to understand that as just basically coming from this false view of self, et cetera, and not to sort of get all guilty about that.

123
00:12:58,126 --> 00:13:01,573
It's just, shall we say, a reaction.

124
00:13:01,994 --> 00:13:05,480
But again, it's this ability to rise above it.

125
00:13:07,148 --> 00:13:11,835
These I've picked up from various things that I've read.

126
00:13:11,916 --> 00:13:14,460
There's what's known as empathy bias.

127
00:13:15,039 --> 00:13:31,265
So if a nurse, for instance, is in a ward, but she has a, or he has a rather particular connection with one of the patients, then you might find the nurse sort of visiting them slightly more often and

128
00:13:31,245 --> 00:13:38,556
I'm not really heeding what somebody is calling from the other side of the ward because they don't particularly like them.

129
00:13:38,897 --> 00:13:40,884
So there's always that going on.

130
00:13:42,215 --> 00:13:43,697
Codependency.

131
00:13:43,817 --> 00:13:55,200
So that's a bit of a problem because if a person is getting a lot of self-esteem from helping, it's very difficult for them not to stop.

132
00:13:55,681 --> 00:14:02,754
And so often they're feeding the person who's actually suffering so that they don't have to stop doing good.

133
00:14:03,173 --> 00:14:15,018
I knew a mother, you see, who had, her son was a drug addict and she was always helping him, you know, like paying for his rent when he didn't have it and buying food for him, you know.

134
00:14:15,457 --> 00:14:19,868
And I said to her, I said, well, what you're doing is just feeding his habit financially.

135
00:14:19,908 --> 00:14:21,991
She says, yes, she says, but I'm his mother.

136
00:14:23,508 --> 00:14:31,758
So she couldn't get over that sort of feeling of guilt if she stopped helping her son.

137
00:14:31,958 --> 00:14:33,585
But it would have been the best thing to do that.

138
00:14:35,590 --> 00:14:42,783
I think you have to be careful when you are dealing with a long situation of somebody whom you're looking after, perhaps.

139
00:14:43,684 --> 00:14:51,500
And that's, of course, your emotional boundary to know when you're being taken advantage of, you know, even perhaps abused, you know.

140
00:14:54,205 --> 00:14:57,530
So that's something else to be careful about.

141
00:14:58,573 --> 00:15:07,250
And within all and sometimes we find ourselves becoming very involved in a compassionate

142
00:15:08,075 --> 00:15:11,057
in a compassionate charity.

143
00:15:12,058 --> 00:15:27,135
I'm just thinking of people who get very much involved with refugees, on the side completely of the refugees, and they can have a lack of recognizing what it's doing to them.

144
00:15:27,216 --> 00:15:35,144
So you get that sort of burnout and then a resentment from it, what they call compassion fatigue.

145
00:15:35,615 --> 00:15:42,160
And I think that's easy to fall into just as, because, you know, there's so much bad news.

146
00:15:42,841 --> 00:16:01,658
Everywhere you go, there's just bad news, you know, and, and you can, you can feel your heart going out to various situations and various people, but in this, but in the end, you've got to recognize that, well, enough's enough, you know, stop feeding, stop feeding all the bad news and try and find some good news.

147
00:16:04,080 --> 00:16:04,440
And,

148
00:16:08,673 --> 00:16:35,135
Yeah, sometimes overemphasizing that sort of helping people and becoming too attached to somebody might blind us to the fact that we might be, in a sense, not allowing them to reflect upon their own situation and take moral stance about themselves.

149
00:16:35,115 --> 00:16:38,044
I'm just thinking of an ADHD.

150
00:16:38,085 --> 00:16:41,575
What have I got here?

151
00:16:41,615 --> 00:16:43,640
Just a minute.

152
00:16:45,712 --> 00:16:49,518
Yeah, that sort of hyperactive, impulsive behavior.

153
00:16:49,557 --> 00:16:56,566
And somebody, you know, might, for instance, just get into gambling because of it.

154
00:16:57,626 --> 00:17:00,190
And we're being we're being over compassionate.

155
00:17:00,210 --> 00:17:00,931
We're not actually.

156
00:17:02,111 --> 00:17:09,161
It's the problem with medicalizing something is that the person then drops their moral responsibility towards themselves.

157
00:17:09,221 --> 00:17:10,201
You know, oh, well, I'm.

158
00:17:10,367 --> 00:17:17,499
I'm at ADHD, you know, or I'm on the whatever it is.

159
00:17:17,538 --> 00:17:22,886
So it's a case of also recognizing that we might be making excuses for them.

160
00:17:24,769 --> 00:17:29,877
We might be therefore avoiding difficult conversations, you know.

161
00:17:30,482 --> 00:17:34,327
So all these things are sort of things to be wary of.

162
00:17:34,989 --> 00:17:38,813
And it's not as though we have to go around with a great big list.

163
00:17:38,853 --> 00:17:42,417
Every time we help somebody, you've got to have your list out just in case you're doing something wrong.

164
00:17:43,818 --> 00:17:58,076
It's more in the sense of recognizing that when we are being compassionate, there's probably some undertone that's going on there, coming from this wrong sense of ego, this wrong sense of self.

165
00:17:58,057 --> 00:18:03,233
But there is, of course, great virtues to be had from compassion.

166
00:18:03,816 --> 00:18:07,307
And one of them is patience, of course, which we've dealt with, you know.

167
00:18:07,726 --> 00:18:14,733
One of the telltales, I think, of compassion is that you're actually deeply happy about it.

168
00:18:14,753 --> 00:18:18,678
This is not the happiness of joy or the happiness of buying an ice cream.

169
00:18:19,199 --> 00:18:27,007
This is that sense of an inner worthiness, an inner sense that you're doing the right thing.

170
00:18:27,047 --> 00:18:35,016
It's a deeper sense of joy, which I think you've all experienced at some point or other when we've helped people.

171
00:18:34,996 --> 00:18:37,198
So that's the sign of compassion.

172
00:18:37,218 --> 00:18:38,318
We're not supposed to be suffering.

173
00:18:38,920 --> 00:18:40,922
When you're being compassionate, you're not supposed to be suffering.

174
00:18:41,221 --> 00:18:42,522
I mean, that would be ridiculous.

175
00:18:43,183 --> 00:18:57,498
And in fact, this confusion came up when I was in a particular meditation center where they had eventually, lay people had been discussing, they eventually came to the conclusion that the Buddha could not have been compassionate because he'd have been suffering.

176
00:18:58,179 --> 00:19:00,701
How ridiculous that is, is it?

177
00:19:00,721 --> 00:19:04,664
So we have to be careful there.

178
00:19:06,198 --> 00:19:18,240
I'll just mention it because it's a whole subject on its own, but the Tibetan practice of Tonglen is all about making that connection with others.

179
00:19:19,962 --> 00:19:26,094
Pema Chodron has a very good meditation up on YouTube, an introduction, shall we say.

180
00:19:26,695 --> 00:19:27,497
So I...

181
00:19:28,102 --> 00:19:33,190
I just want, this will appear eventually as a tip.

182
00:19:33,611 --> 00:19:36,494
It'll be the next one, actually, the one for October.

183
00:19:37,276 --> 00:19:40,922
And there you'll be able to pick up these connections.

184
00:19:41,702 --> 00:19:43,967
But I do want to mention this one point where

185
00:19:44,555 --> 00:19:49,983
the Buddha came across a monk who was actually suffering from dysentery.

186
00:19:50,324 --> 00:19:54,230
So he was completely in his whatever, you know.

187
00:19:54,711 --> 00:19:59,638
And when he saw the sick monk and asked him, you know, well, who's attending to you?

188
00:19:59,659 --> 00:20:00,220
He said, nobody.

189
00:20:00,681 --> 00:20:01,501
And then he said, why?

190
00:20:01,521 --> 00:20:03,746
He says, well, I don't attend to monks.

191
00:20:03,766 --> 00:20:06,309
So the monks don't attend to me.

192
00:20:06,289 --> 00:20:16,490
So he and Ananda looked after this monk and then he gathered the monks together and he said to them, look, you have no mother, you have no father who might tend to you.

193
00:20:16,809 --> 00:20:19,375
If you don't tend to one another, then who will tend to you?

194
00:20:19,855 --> 00:20:23,303
So whoever would tend to me should tend to the sick.

195
00:20:23,282 --> 00:20:33,256
So there he's making, you know, getting them to make a connection to the Buddha, to himself, you know, like whoever is attending to somebody who's sick, you are attending to a Buddha.

196
00:20:33,757 --> 00:20:39,284
Now, you might not take that literally as the Buddha himself, but to the Buddha within, right?

197
00:20:40,384 --> 00:20:43,249
To that within us, which is transcendent.

198
00:20:43,819 --> 00:20:48,183
And then he goes on and gives a whole list of people who should be looking after them.

199
00:20:50,325 --> 00:20:53,548
So he was involved in that.

200
00:20:53,587 --> 00:20:56,089
So now I'm going on a bit, I'm afraid.

201
00:20:56,951 --> 00:21:00,534
What I want to do now is just do a bit of compassion practice.

202
00:21:01,355 --> 00:21:05,157
And I'm going to actually share this with you.

203
00:21:07,359 --> 00:21:08,099
Just one second.

204
00:21:12,324 --> 00:21:13,724
Yeah, the screen, I think.

205
00:21:16,337 --> 00:21:16,898
That's the one.

206
00:21:18,682 --> 00:21:20,626
OK, I'm hoping you can see that.

207
00:21:21,849 --> 00:21:25,336
So these are the blessings that we do here in the morning puja.

208
00:21:26,058 --> 00:21:28,604
And can everybody see that?

209
00:21:28,644 --> 00:21:30,989
Just give me somebody give me a thumbs up, Paul.

210
00:21:31,009 --> 00:21:31,349
Thank you.

211
00:21:31,509 --> 00:21:31,750
Right.

212
00:21:32,251 --> 00:21:36,961
OK, so the idea is that as we go through this list.

213
00:21:36,942 --> 00:21:42,269
We can bring up a phrase which expresses our compassion.

214
00:21:42,628 --> 00:21:48,277
So the one that's normally used is, may your sufferings lessen, may all your sufferings come to an end.

215
00:21:48,457 --> 00:21:57,548
So that would come out of the Visuddhimagga, this compendium of Buddhism written by Buddhaghosa in the Middle Ages.

216
00:21:58,851 --> 00:22:04,417
Or you can make up some other phrase that makes sense to you.

217
00:22:04,397 --> 00:22:09,022
But just for this, it might be good just to stay with this one here.

218
00:22:10,084 --> 00:22:13,547
And then as I go through the list, just keep repeating that.

219
00:22:13,708 --> 00:22:16,830
And then we'll do the six directions.

220
00:22:17,111 --> 00:22:20,354
And then after that, we'll just slip into the meditation.

221
00:22:20,555 --> 00:22:28,061
You can continue doing it or return to Vipassana.

222
00:22:28,082 --> 00:22:28,403
Okay.

223
00:22:32,666 --> 00:22:33,627
Okay.

224
00:22:34,147 --> 00:22:43,611
So if we just settle for a moment.

225
00:22:43,631 --> 00:22:47,500
So we can bring to mind anyone we know who's having a hard time.

226
00:23:08,167 --> 00:23:14,074
At this moment, there are people who are suffering from physical, severe physical or mental disease.

227
00:23:26,306 --> 00:23:33,653
There are people in the process of dying and those who have died and left grieving family, relatives and friends.

228
00:23:47,385 --> 00:23:50,930
There are people going hungry, homeless and destitute.

229
00:24:05,807 --> 00:24:10,592
There are those struggling with personal and interpersonal difficulties.

230
00:24:25,507 --> 00:24:27,611
There are all the victims of prejudices.

231
00:24:27,672 --> 00:24:44,105
All those caught up in wars and repressive regimes.

232
00:24:58,108 --> 00:24:59,612
and those being tortured.

233
00:25:14,558 --> 00:25:19,627
There are all the criminals, oppressors and all who willingly do harm.

234
00:25:36,247 --> 00:25:41,030
all those suffering from natural disasters and climate crisis.

235
00:26:00,308 --> 00:26:05,493
All sentient beings have been cruelly treated and unnecessarily slaughtered.

236
00:26:17,152 --> 00:26:19,775
and all who find life meaningless.

237
00:26:32,971 --> 00:26:42,923
Now we can continue with the ten directions to all beings in front of us who are suffering.

238
00:26:53,720 --> 00:26:55,584
All beings behind us.

239
00:27:07,648 --> 00:27:09,432
All beings to our left.

240
00:27:22,255 --> 00:27:24,018
All beings to our right.

241
00:27:36,519 --> 00:27:38,644
All beings below us.

242
00:27:50,317 --> 00:27:52,501
All beings above us.

243
00:28:05,605 --> 00:28:08,631
And to all beings in all directions.

244
00:28:19,309 --> 00:28:24,307
So feel free to continue this practice or just sit in vipassana.

